S'{{Other people2|Michael Bishop (disambiguation){{!}}Michael Bishop}}\n\n{{Infobox congressman\n|birthname      = Mike Bishop \n|name           = Mike Bishop\n|image          = \n|state          = [[Michigan]]\n| office        = Member-elect of the<br>[[U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Michigan\'s 8th congressional district|Michigan\'s 8th district]] \n| term_start    = January 3, 2015\n| term_end      = \n| succeeding    = [[Mike Rogers (Michigan politician)|Mike Rogers]]\n| succeeded     = \n| order2        = 13th\n| office2       = Michigan Senate#Majority Leadership{{!}}Majority Leader of the Michigan Senate\n| term_start2   = January 1, 2007\n| term_end2     = December 31, 2010\n| predecessor2  = [[Ken Sikkema]]\n| successor2    = [[Randy Richardville]]\n| state_senate3 =  Michigan\n| district3     =  12th\n| term_start3   =  January 1, 2003\n| term_end3     =  December 31, 2010\n| predecessor3  =  [[Alan Sanborn]]\n| successor3    =  [[Jim Marleau]]\n| state_house4  =  Michigan\n| district4     =  45th\n| term_start4   =  January 1, 1999\n| term_end4     =  December 31, 2002\n| predecessor4  =  Penny Crissman\n| successor4    =  John Garfield\n| birth_name    = Michael D. Bishop\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1967|03|18}}\n| birth_place   = [[Almont, Michigan]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse        = Cristina Bishop \n| children      = 3\n| alma_mater    = [[Detroit College of Law]]<br>[[University of Michigan]]\n| profession    = Attorney}}\n\n\'\'\'Michael D. "Mike" Bishop\'\'\' (born March 18, 1967) is a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] politician from the [[U.S. state]] of [[Michigan]]. He is a former member and [[majority leader]] of the [[Michigan Senate]].<ref>[http://legislature.mi.gov/(S(xkgik3j0k3pt4255nehxgjiy))/documents/2009-2010/michiganmanual/2009-MM-p0145-p0145.pdf 2009-2010 Michigan Manual: State Senator Michael D. Bishop]</ref> \n\nOn November 4, 2014, Bishop defeated Democratic challenger Eric Schertzing for Michigan\'s 8th Congressional District.<ref>[http://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/elections/2014/11/04/michigan-congress-eighth-district-election-results/18491127 Bishop defeats Schertzing for 8th District congressional race], detroitnews.com; accessed November 30, 2014.</ref> Bishop will be sworn in January 3, 2015. \n\nBishop, of [[Rochester, Michigan]], was elected to the Senate after two terms in the [[Michigan House of Representatives]]. He was sworn into office in January 2003 to represent the 12th District constituency, a seat which was previously held by his father, Donald Bishop. The 12th District encompasses the communities of [[Auburn Hills, Michigan|Auburn Hills]], [[Keego Harbor, Michigan|Keego Harbor]], [[Lake Angelus, Michigan|Lake Angelus]], [[Sylvan Lake, Michigan|Sylvan Lake]], [[Pontiac, Michigan|Pontiac]], [[Rochester, Michigan|Rochester]] and [[Rochester Hills, Michigan|Rochester Hills]], and the townships of [[Addison Township, Michigan|Addison]], [[Independence Township, Michigan|Independence]], [[Oakland Township, Michigan|Oakland]], [[Orion Township, Michigan|Orion]] and [[Oxford Township, Michigan|Oxford]]. \n\nBefore his time as majority leader, Bishop served as assistant majority leader. He was chosen to be chairman of the Banking and Financial Institutions Committee and vice chairman of both the Gaming and Casino Oversight Committee and Judiciary Committee. During his four-year tenure in the Michigan House, he served as vice chairman of the Commerce Committee. A 1989 honors graduate of the [[University of Michigan]], Bishop received his law degree from the [[Detroit College of Law]] in 1993, and is a partner in his own [[Oakland County, Michigan|Oakland County]] law firm. He is also a licensed [[real estate broker]] and owner of two local real estate businesses (Freedom Realty, Inc. and Pro Management, Inc.).\n\nBishop is a member of the [[American Bar Association]], [[State Bar of Michigan]], Washington, D.C., Bar, Bar of the Supreme Court of the United States, Oakland County Bar Association, Michigan Association of Realtors, and [[National Association of Realtors]]. He served on the Municipal Law and Business Law committees of the Oakland County Bar Association and is a member of the [[National Association of Sportsmen Legislators]]. \n\nMichigan\'s [[term limits]] prohibited Bishop from seeking re-election in 2010 to the Senate. He ran for [[Oakland County, Michigan#Oakland County elected officials|Prosecutor]] of [[Oakland County, Michigan|Oakland County]] in 2012 but lost to Democratic incumbent Jessica R. Cooper. He was speculated to challenge incumbent [[Governor of Michigan]] [[Rick Snyder]] in the Republican primary [[Michigan gubernatorial election, 2014|in 2014]] but ruled out doing so.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theoaklandpress.com/articles/2013/06/24/news/politics/doc51c8539ba04f8636931423.txt?viewmode=fullstory|title=Former Michigan GOP Senate Majority Leader Mike Bishop: \'I\'m not running for governor\'|date=June 24, 2013|accessdate=June 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nBishop is married and has three children.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{CongLinks | ballot = Michael_Bishop | votesmart = 20157 | followthemoney = 11750 }}\n\n{{MI-FedRep}}\n{{U.S. Michigan Representatives}}\n\n{{Persondata <!-- Metadata: see [[Wikipedia:Persondata]]. -->\n| NAME              = Bishop, Michael D.\n| ALTERNATIVE NAMES = Bishop, Mike\n| SHORT DESCRIPTION = American politician\n| DATE OF BIRTH     = March 18, 1967\n| PLACE OF BIRTH    = [[Almont, Michigan]], U.S.\n| DATE OF DEATH     =\n| PLACE OF DEATH    =\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bishop, Mike}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Detroit College of Law alumni]